With an imminent IRA statement expected, British officials anticipate a shift in Northern Irish politics.
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams urged the IRA to embrace democracy and end violence.
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern emphasized the need for a clear response from the IRA to advance peace efforts.
The Good Friday peace deal, established in 1998, aimed to end sectarian violence.
Calls for the IRA to disarm and disband have been made by political leaders.
The IRA's actions will determine the future of Catholic-Protestant cooperation in Northern Ireland.
